GER100Y1-Y-20179.courseDescription: This is the language course to take if you have had no previous experience of the German language. The emphasis is on comprehension, speaking, reading, writing, vocabulary and basic grammar. This course can be counted towards all programs in German. Note: Students with any previous knowledge of German are REQUIRED to take a placement test offered at the department.
GER100Y1-Y-20179.exclusion: Senior high school German or equivalent. Note: Students with any previous knowledge of German are required to take a placement test offered at the department.
GER100Y1-Y-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is for students with no prior background in German. If you have had any background in German, you are required to take a 30 minute written placement test. To register for the test, please contact gayle.grisdale@utoronto.ca.

GER101H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course is intended for students with some prior knowledge of German. It is equivalent to the Spring Term of GER100Y1. The emphasis is on comprehension, speaking, reading, writing, vocabulary and basic grammar.
GER101H1-S-20179.exclusion: Senior high school German or equivalent. GER100Y.
GER101H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is for students with some background in German. You are required to take a 30 minute written placement test to determine your level. To enrol in this course and register for the test, please contact gayle.grisdale@utoronto.ca.

GER102Y1-Y-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is for Graduate Students wishing to take Introduction to German I.  You must get your Add/Drop dates from from your home department signed and brought to the German Department for signature. Email the German Department if you have any questions at gayle.grisdale@utoronto.ca.

GER150H1-F-20179.courseDescription: This course taught in English is intended for students who are unfamiliar with German culture. It examines historical, political and cultural developments in Germany from about 1871 to the present focusing on literary and non-literary texts. Note: This course is required for the major and specialist program, and can only be taken within the first two years. In later years it may be substituted with GER310H1.

GER150H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course taught in English is intended for students who are unfamiliar with German culture. It examines historical, political and cultural developments in Germany from about 1871 to the present focusing on literary and non-literary texts. Note: This course is required for the major and specialist program, and can only be taken within the first two years. In later years it may be substituted with GER310H1.

GER200Y1-Y-20179.courseDescription: This course continues the work done in GER100Y1 / GER101H1. It further expands on basic grammar and vocabulary, practice in comprehension, composition, and conversation.
GER200Y1-Y-20179.prerequisite: GER100Y1/GER101H1 or German placement test, Senior high school German or equivalent

GER205H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course offers a transition from the language courses to the topic courses on the 300-level. It introduces students to German literature and provides them with working methods and analytical tools relevant for the study of German literary texts in the original German. Note: This course is required for the major and specialist program
GER205H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER220H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course taught in English is an introduction to major authors of German literature, such as J.W. Goethe, F. Kafka, T. Mann, G. Grass, C. Wolf and E.S. zdamar, focusing on their key works and introducing central topics.
GER220H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in English.

GER250H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Focusing on a specific era of film production (e.g.Weimar cinema, Nazi era and postwar, feminist filmmaking, New German Cinema or Postwall), this course explores the relationship between social movements and film form and style. Taught in English. Cross-listed with the Cinema Studies Program Innis College.
GER250H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in English.

GER260Y1-Y-20179.courseDescription: This course introduces Yiddish language, literature, music, theater, and cinema through interactive multi-media seminars, designed to build proficiency in reading, writing and comprehending. No prior knowledge of Yiddish is required.

GER270H1-F-20179.courseTitle: Money and Economy in German Literature and Culture (E)
GER270H1-F-20179.courseDescription: In this course, we examine key literary, philosophical, and cultural texts, in order to understand how modern culture approaches problems such as property, debt, and exchange value.
GER270H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in English.

GER272H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course introduces students to basic concepts and vocabulary necessary for the German business context. All the language skills (reading, writing, listening, and speaking) will be practiced in appropriate business contexts.
GER272H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER300Y1-Y-20179.courseDescription: Continuing the work done in GER100Y1 and GER200Y1, this course offers German at the intermediate level focusing on extension of vocabulary, specific problems of grammar, essay-writing, reading and conversation. The Department reserves the right to place students in the appropriate course in the series GER200Y1 and GER300Y1.

GER305H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Building on the work of GER205H1, this course offers a survey of German literature and culture from the eighteenth to the twentieth century. Within a chronological framework, students read and analyze excerpts from representative works of major German writers. Note: This course is required for the major and specialist program, and should be taken concurrently with GER300Y1
GER305H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER310H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course focuses on contemporary German culture as expressed through a variety of media. It approaches Germany and Germany's position within Europe and the world mainly (but not exclusively) through non-literary texts. Note: This course may count as a substitute course for the required GER150H1; please inquire in advance.
GER310H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER320H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Goethe and his contemporaries saw themselves faced with a rapidly changing world. This course examines the innovative literary experiments they developed in response to these changing times.
GER320H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER322H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Franz Kafka's texts are read in the literary, historical, and philosophical context of fin-de-sicle Prague and central Europe.
GER322H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER323H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Focusing roughly on the period from 1918 to 1945, this course examines literary and artistic movements like Dada, Bauhaus, the Golden Age in German film in the decades between World War I and Nazism.
GER323H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER332H1-S-20179.courseDescription: An analysis of the artistic confrontation with deviance, madness, and outsiders. The course covers expressions of this confrontation in a variety of genres.
GER332H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER336H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course offers an exploration of the cultural developments of one of the most exciting capitals of the world, from the Bismarckian era to German reunification and beyond.
GER336H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER350H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course presents students with a survey of the history and development of the German cinema. It examines major trends of German cinematography focusing on thematic and formal aspects.

GER360H1-F-20179.courseDescription: The course conducted in Yiddish offers a review of basic grammar, stylistics, study of short literary texts.

GER361H1-F-20179.courseDescription: An overview of the major figures and tendencies in modern Yiddish literature and culture from the beginning of the 19th century to the present. Readings (in English) of modern Yiddish prose, poetry, drama and cinema.

GER367H1-F-20179.courseTitle: Topics in Yiddish or German Jewish Literature and Culture
GER367H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Topics in modern Yiddish or German Jewish literature and culture from the beginning of the 19th century to the present, featuring a selection of readings of modern Yiddish prose, poetry, drama and cinema. Taught in English and open to students across disciplines.
GER367H1-F-20179.prerequisite: Completion of a minimum of 4.0 FCEs

GER400H1-F-20179.courseDescription: This is a course for advanced learners of German reviewing complex features of the language and introducing them to aspects of German stylistics. The emphasis lies on oral and written communication.

GER411H1-F-20179.courseDescription: The course familiarizes students with some of the key issues in critical theory today. Focusing on current debates, it will provide the background to these debates.
GER411H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in English.

GER423H1-F-20179.courseDescription: This course investigates contemporary German culture by paying attention to its other or alternate voices and perspectives, i.e. those not usually prevalent in mainstream cultural and sociopolitical discourses.
GER423H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER426H1-F-20179.courseDescription: This course offers an introduction to the language, literature and culture of Medieval Germany. The reading and translation of exemplary medieval German texts will introduce students to Middle High German and provide an insight into epochal concepts like courtly love and chivalry as well as courtly and monastic designs of identity.
GER426H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: This course is taught in German.

GER462H1-F-20179.courseDescription: This course conducted entirely in Yiddish focuses on advanced reading, writing, vocabulary and conversation, the study of poetry, short fiction, and memoir literature by leading authors. Selected advanced grammatical topics are presented in conjunction with the study of texts.

GER462H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course conducted entirely in Yiddish focuses on advanced reading, writing, vocabulary and conversation, the study of poetry, short fiction, and memoir literature by leading authors. Selected advanced grammatical topics are presented in conjunction with the study of texts.

GER490H1-F-20179.courseDescription: A reading & research project in Germanic literature and/or culture involving a substantive research component. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
GER490H1-F-20179.prerequisite: Advanced status and permission of department. Note: permission needs to be obtained by May 1st for the Fall Term and by Nov. 1st for the Spring Term
GER490H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: To enrol in this course,  please contact gayle.grisdale@utoronto.ca

GER490H1-S-20179.courseDescription: A reading & research project in Germanic literature and/or culture involving a substantive research component. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
GER490H1-S-20179.prerequisite: Advanced status and permission of department. Note: permission needs to be obtained by May 1st for the Fall Term and by Nov. 1st for the Spring Term
GER490H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: To enrol in this course,  please contact gayle.grisdale@utoronto.ca

GER491Y1-Y-20179.courseDescription: A scholarly project chosen by the student and supervised by a member of the staff. The form of the project and the manner of its execution are determined in consultation with the supervisor. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
GER491Y1-Y-20179.prerequisite: Prerequisite: Advanced status and permission of department. Note: project proposals need to be submitted by June 1st
GER491Y1-Y-20179.webTimetableInstructions: To enrol in this course,  please contact gayle.grisdale@utoronto.ca
